reason.tex:
%text Differentiation has the \underline\text{product rule} \[ \quad \frac{d}{dx}f(x)g(x) = f'(x) g(x) + f(x) g'(x) \]
And integration has \underline\text{integration by parts}
\[ \int f(x)g(x) dx = f(x)\int g(x) dx - \int \left[ f'(x) \int g(x) dx\right] dx \]
\underline\text{But what is $f(x)$ in, say, \[\int x\sin x\cdot dx\]}? Is it $f(x) = x$ or $f(x) = \sin x$?
There is no right or wrong answer. Only better answers. And there is a nice \underline\text{rule of thumb -- called ILATE} to help you decide which function to pick as $f(x)$ and which as $g(x)$
Simply take the two functions and compare it with the table below.
\underline\text{The first matching function is $f(x)$} \underline\text{and the second is (automatically) $g(x)$}
% \begin{tabular}{c|c|c} \hline & \text{Meaning} & \text{Example} \\ \hline I & \text{Inverse Trig. function} & \sin^{-1} x, \tan^{-1}x \\ \hline L & \text{Logarithmic function} & \log x \\ \hline A & \text{Algebraic function} & x^2, 4x^7 \\ \hline T & \text{Trigonometric function} & \sin x, \cos x \\ \hline E & \text{Exponential function} & e^x, 7^x \\ \hline \end{tabular}
